Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation and confirm:**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` (hardware/gesture back) and handle the Shell back button via `BackButtonBehavior`:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            Dispatcher.Dispatch(async () =>
            {
                bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                    "Unsaved Changes",
                    "Discard changes and go back?",
                    "Discard", "Stay");

                if (leave)
                    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
            });
            return true; // cancel the default navigation
        }
        return base.OnBackButtonPressed();
    }
}
```

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button in XAML:**

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior
            TextOverride="Cancel"
            Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

Then in your view model (or code-behind):

```csharp
public ICommand BackCommand { get; }

public EditProductPageViewModel()
{
    BackCommand = new Command(async () =>
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "Discard changes and go back?",
                "Discard", "Stay");
            if (!leave) return;
        }
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    });
}
```

**Key points:**
- `OnBackButtonPressed` handles Android hardware/gesture back — return `true` to cancel.
- `BackButtonBehavior.Command` replaces the Shell toolbar back button tap — it won't navigate unless you explicitly call `GoToAsync("..")`.
- `TextOverride="Cancel"` replaces the arrow with text. Use `IconOverride` if you want a custom icon instead.
